It is a question of opinion whether cyber-attacks are more or less harmful than physical ones. Physical assaults, on the other hand, may inflict instant damage to persons, whilst cyber-attacks can have longer-term implications. A physical assault on a building, for example, might result in immediate damage and harm, but a cyber-attack on a company's network can result in the loss of sensitive data as well as financial loss. Cyber-attacks, on the other hand, might have rapid implications. A cyber-attack on a hospital's network, for example, might impair crucial care delivery, possibly inflicting injury to patients. Furthermore, cyber-attacks may have a considerably broader reach than physical assaults since they can target people all over the world. Cybercrime is expected to cost the globe $6 trillion per year by 2021, according to Cybersecurity Ventures research. This covers the cost of data breaches, cyber espionage, and key infrastructure interruptions. The methods available to safeguard the cyber-world from these assaults are growing increasingly sophisticated, but they are not without flaws. Firewalls, antivirus software, and intrusion detection systems, for example, may assist to avoid cyber-attacks, but they are not perfect. Furthermore, firms may establish security procedures such as two-factor authentication and frequent security upgrades, although these precautions are not always efficiently applied. A nation-state might employ cyber-attacks to impair key infrastructure, such as power grids, transportation systems, and banking networks, in a cyber warfare scenario. This might create significant disruption and perhaps serious injury. A nation-state might also deploy cyber-attacks to steal important information or impair its opponents' communication infrastructure. It is impossible to predict when a cyberwar is likely to occur, but it is apparent that the danger of cyber-attacks is rising. According to a Center for Strategic and International Studies research, the number of cyber incidents impacting vital infrastructure has climbed from one per month on average in 2010 to more than 200 per month in 2018. Finally, cyber-attacks may be just as harmful as physical assaults since they can inflict instant injury, financial loss, and long-term implications. The methods available to defend the cyber-world are improving, but they are not perfect. Cyberwarfare is a serious danger that may disrupt communication infrastructure, inflict widespread disruption, and steal important information. The frequency of cyber events impacting vital infrastructure is rising, and it is difficult to predict when a cyberwar would occur. 